  "prompt": "A triangle has angles in the ratio 2:3:4. What is the size of the smallest of the three angles?",
  "response": "Let's solve this step by step:\n\n1) First, recall that the sum of angles in a triangle is always 180\u00b0\n\n2) Let the smallest angle be x\u00b0. Then the other two angles will be 3x/2 and 2x according to the given ratio\n\n3) We know these must add up to 180\u00b0:\n   \u2022 x + 3x/2 + 2x = 180\u00b0\n\n4) Simplify the left side of the equation:\n   \u2022 x + 3x/2 + 2x = x(1 + 3/2 + 2)\n   \u2022 x(1 + 3/2 + 2) = x(4.5)\n   \u2022 x(4.5) = 180\u00b0\n\n5) Solve for x:\n   \u2022 x = 180\u00b0 \u00f7 4.5\n   \u2022 x = 40\u00b0\n\n6) Let's verify:\n   \u2022 Smallest angle: 40\u00b0\n   \u2022 Next angle: 3(40\u00b0)/2 = 60\u00b0\n   \u2022 Largest angle: 2(40\u00b0) = 80\u00b0\n   \u2022 40\u00b0 + 60\u00b0 + 80\u00b0 = 180\u00b0 \u2713\n\nThe answer is 40.",
